  "prompt": "Is it normal to have a dark ring around the iris of my eye?",
  "response": "A dark ring around the iris, often referred to as a **limbal ring**, is a common and generally normal feature of the eye. Here's a breakdown:\n\n*   **What it is:** The limbal ring is a dark-colored ring around the edge of the iris where the iris meets the sclera (the white part of the eye).\n\n*   **Why it exists:** It's due to differences in the collagen structure and pigmentation at the limbus (the border between the cornea and sclera).\n\n*   **Commonality:** Many people have visible limbal rings, although the prominence can vary depending on factors like age, ethnicity, and genetics.\n\n*   **Association with health:** Generally, a limbal ring is not indicative of a health problem.\n\n*   **Perceived beauty:** Some studies have suggested that prominent limbal rings are subconsciously associated with youth and health, and therefore considered attractive.\n\n**When to be concerned:**\nWhile usually normal, there are situations where changes in the appearance around the iris warrant medical attention:\n\n*   **Sudden appearance of a dark ring, especially if accompanied by pain, vision changes, or other symptoms:** This could indicate a different condition and needs evaluation.\n*   **Significant change in the color or thickness of the ring.**\n*   **Any other unusual changes in your eye's appearance or vision.**\n\n**In summary:** A limbal ring is typically a normal and benign feature of the eye. However, if you notice any sudden changes or have any concerns, it's always best to consult with an eye doctor to rule out any potential underlying issues.",
